The memo argues for the president's authority to conduct military operations against terrorists and their supporters to protect the US, even preemptively.
It grants Bush the power to attack groups like Abu Sayef and Hezbollah.
Gonzales, responsible for the legal framework, defended Bush's stance on defending Americans from terrorists.
The administration downplayed the memos' significance, but critics argue against the torture methods used.
The White House's imperial view on presidential authority clashes with legal boundaries.
The issue of prisoner abuse remains unresolved, with drafts of measures risking endorsement of questionable practices.
